task_description:
In the  experiment, each participant is given 36 different proposals to respond to. Each is designated by a trial number in the data set This gives 36 instances for the learnable parameters to be trained. There is also a pretask where the participant finds a number of tokens that correspond to their contribution to the group. This is designated by the variable "token_self". The other variable, "token_opp", is the number of tokens found the opponent's and represents the opoonents contribution to the shared pot that will be later divided by the opponent.

Note that in each trial there is a variable amount of money in the combined earning, so that two equal split_self variables do not represent the same "fairness".

Below is the description of each variable in the dataset, which will be followed by information about the data type of the variable:

trial_type = how much was the contribution [1 = equal, 2 = opponent more, 3 = participant more]
trial_role = the role of the participant [1 = responder, 2 = proposer]
token_opp = number of tokens found by the opponent
token_self = number of tokens found by the participant
combined_earning = amount of money earned in total (note that each token found is £3)
split_opp = the proposed share of the opponent (in £)
split_self = the proposed share for the participant (in £)
splitperc_opp = same but in %
split_perc_self = same but in %
accept = whether the participant responded accept (1) or reject (0)
accepted_amount = if accepted, what is the amount gain (in £)
accepted_perc = same as above but in %
proposed_perc = when participant is the proposer, what is the % proposed to the opponent

lambda_param.description: Sensitivity parameter for inequity aversion. It scales the penalty for the amount by which the offer falls short of the fairness standard.

split_self.description: Monetary share proposed to the participant (responder) in each trial.

model_summary: The model calculates the utility of accepting an offer as the sum of a baseline bias and the monetary offer, minus a fairness penalty applied when the offer is below the fair share (computed based on the participant’s tokens and the combined earning). Two learnable parameters control the bias (beta) and sensitivity to unfairness (lambda_param), ensuring the model can capture responder behavior under inequity aversion.
full_reasoning:
Step 1: Reasoning about the mechanisms and structure

• Key psychological mechanisms:
  – Responders compare the monetary offer (split_self) to a fairness standard.
  – The fairness standard is assumed to be proportional to the responder’s contribution relative to the combined contributions from both players (i.e. token_self relative to token_self + token_opp) multiplied by the combined earning.
  – When the received amount is below this fairness expectation, the responder experiences a penalty (inequity aversion) which lowers the subjective utility.
  – A baseline bias (or intercept) captures any extra tendency toward acceptance independent of the monetary offer.

• Interaction of mechanisms:
  – The subjective utility of accepting an offer is built by adding the actual monetary offer (split_self) together with a baseline bias.
  – If the monetary offer is below the fair share, the difference is penalized by a sensitivity (lambda_param) to unfairness (inequity aversion). Offers above the fair share are not “rewarded” for being generous in this model – only under-cut fairness is penalized.

• Mathematical form:
  – We compute a fairness standard (fair_share) in each trial as:
       fair_share = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning
  – The utility of acceptance is then defined as:
       U_accept = beta + split_self – lambda_param * max(fair_share – split_self, 0)
  – The max(.) operator ensures that only when the offer is below the fairness standard is a penalty applied.

• Learnable parameters:
  – beta: baseline bias in utility, capturing predisposition toward acceptance independent of fairness.
  – lambda_param: sensitivity to deviations below the fairness standard (inequity aversion).  
Both parameters are chosen with generous finite bounds.

• Mapping to observable behavior:
  – The model uses observed quantities (split_self, token_self, token_opp, combined_earning) from the dataset.
  – Each trial’s computed utility (U_accept) determines the subjective value associated with accepting an offer.
  – Negative utility values correspond to unlikely actions (and later, choice probabilities will be derived from these utilities via a stochastic choice rule such as a softmax with a temperature parameter handled externally).


Below is the formal specification:

<MODEL>
U_accept = beta + split_self - lambda_param * max((token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning - split_self, 0)
</MODEL>
